%md # Load GS Data to HDFS When we excute the `SELECT count(countryName) FROM wdi_gs` query in wdi_gs, it will take longer time than we excute `SELECT count(countryName) FROM wdi_csv_text` in wdi_csv_text. This is because we store the data are stored in GS, everytime it will be transferred from GS to the hadoop cluster everytime we are running the query.
First time we run the `SELECT count(countryName) FROM wdi_csv_text` it takes almost same time as wdi_gs do. Second time it has a shorter time to execute the query. This is mainly because we stored the data into our HDFS, for second time we run the query, the nodes cached data so we have a better performance than first time.

%md # Parsing issue When we run the `SELECT distinct(indicatorcode)` in wdi_csv_text files, we can see that there is a parsing issue. We can not produce the correct output. By creating a debug table wdi_gs_debug, we conclude that the paresing issue may come from the indicatorname column contains the comma inside the sentence. This case leads the we parse the sentence into 2 columns, the other part of the indicatorname falls into indicatorcode column. So we have the parsing issue.
To solve the issue, our solution is using the OpenCSVSerde to parse the total string. We create a wdi_opencsv_gs to store the data and insert the data in wdi_opencsv_text which is a table located on HDFS. By using OpenCSVSerde, we fixed the paresing issue. But we had a much slower run time for excuting a query compared to the wdi_csv_text. This is because OpenCSVSerde needs extra time to parse the string.
